                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-187-victim1824 t18310217-187-viclabel1123"></join>, and live at No. 72, in <placeName id="t18310217-187-crimeloc1124">Old-street-road</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-187-crimeloc1124" type="placeName" value="Old-street-road"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310217-187-crimeloc1124" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310217-187-off1121 t18310217-187-crimeloc1124"></join>. The prisoner came to me as a lodger on the 27th of September; the last time I saw him was on the morning of the 18th of January - he told me he should return at night, but I did not see him again till he was at Worship-street - I had missed my property a long time before that.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310217-187-person1826">
                  WILLIAM 
                  ATTFIELD
               <interp inst="t18310217-187-person1826" type="surname" value="ATTFIELD"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-187-person1826" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310217-187-person1826" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I took the prisoner on the 22nd of January - he said he lived at No. 3, Old-street-road, but I received information that he was living with an aunt of his in Hoxton Old-town; I went there, and asked what room he lodged in - I was shown up stairs; I looked about for books, but saw none - I saw a gold ring on the mantel-shelf; I did not take it then, but went to Mrs. Brown's - I found forty-eight duplicates in his room; one was for the tea-spoon, and one for a shift - I told Mrs. Brown I had seen a ring at his aunt's, and she said,"That is a ring which I lost;" I went back - the ring was not where I had seen it before, but I found it in the cellar; Mrs. Brown had described it as having been studded with red stones, except in three places, in which she had put black ones.</p>
               <p>
            
